  "solution": {
    "approach": "The required pattern is simply the odds followed by the evens. For each test case we iterate from 1 to N with step 2 to collect odd numbers, then from 2 to N with step 2 for even numbers. The two loops together produce the exact order demanded by the queue‑simulation description. The algorithm is linear in N and uses only a StringBuilder for output, so it easily meets the limits.",
    "timeComplexity": "O(N) per test case, O(total N) over all test cases",
    "spaceComplexity": "O(1) extra besides the output buffer",
    "code": {
      "C": "",
      "C++": "",
      "Java": "import java.io.*;\nimport java.util.*;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));\n        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();\n        int T = Integer.parseInt(br.readLine().trim());\n        for (int tc = 0; tc < T; tc++) {\n            int N = Integer.parseInt(br.readLine().trim());\n            boolean first = true;\n            for (int i = 1; i <= N; i += 2) {\n                if (!first) sb.append(' ');\n                sb.append(i);\n                first = false;\n            }\n            for (int i = 2; i <= N; i += 2) {\n                sb.append(' ').append(i);\n            }\n            if (tc < T - 1) sb.append('\\n');\n        }\n        System.out.print(sb.toString());\n    }\n}",
      "Python3": "",
      "JavaScript": ""
    }
